<subSubSection pageId="21" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,188,1040]" pageId="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,260,285]" pageId="21">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Mandibles brown subapically (
<figureCitation box="[680,748,260,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
B). Epicnemium and prepectus black, only ventral prepectus on sides of medioventral projection dark brownish. Black ring on mesofemur complete. Head about as broad as mesosoma. Gena, lower face and supracoxal stripe of metepimeron moderately setose (
<figureCitation box="[1143,1209,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
A, B). 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21">Clypeus with irregularly distributed points</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[511,583,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
B). 
<emphasis box="[632,1266,367,392]" italics="true" pageId="21">Adtorular carinae thin, appearing as irregular rugae</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1288,1359,367,392]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
A, B). 
<emphasis box="[151,346,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="21">Antennal scrobes</emphasis>
reaching lower margin of median ocellus, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21">virtually as high as eye (0.97×) their upper edge at level with upper ocular line</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[479,546,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
A). 
<emphasis box="[590,1049,439,464]" italics="true" pageId="21">Eyes separated by 0.9× their own height</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1065,1132,439,464]" captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
A). Ocellar ocular distance much shorter than median ocellus diameter (as in 
<figureCitation box="[723,790,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,199,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 5. Brachymeria philornisae Delvare sp. nov. ♀. (A − I paratype TRMO  1, 10 paratype TRMO  10). A, head in dorsal view. B, mesosoma in dorsal view. C, sculpture of mesonotum. D, mesosoma in lateral view. E, propodeum in posterolateral view. F, hind leg. G, sculpture of metafemur. H, hind telotarsus. I, metasoma in dorsal view. J, apex of metasoma in lateral view. Abbreviation: fsa, falcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375993/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
A). Clava tapering with small area of micropilosity (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 8" captionStartId="20.[151,250,1687,1709]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,555,1646]" captionTargetId="figure@20.[151,1436,555,1666]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURE 8. Brachymeria subrugosa Blanchard ♀. A, head in frontal view. B, head in anterolateral view. C, lower face in frontal view. D, pedicel and base of flagellum. E, clava in apicolateral view. Abbreviations: atrc, adtorular carina; stsw subtorular swelling." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375996/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
E). Mesosoma 1.35−1.4× as long as broad. Basal fold of fore wing with 12 or 13 setae. Metasoma 2.01−2.26× as long as broad. Apex of hypopygium emarginate mesally (as in 
<figureCitation box="[856,922,548,573]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1915,1937]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,199,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,193,1893]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 5. Brachymeria philornisae Delvare sp. nov. ♀. (A − I paratype TRMO  1, 10 paratype TRMO  10). A, head in dorsal view. B, mesosoma in dorsal view. C, sculpture of mesonotum. D, mesosoma in lateral view. E, propodeum in posterolateral view. F, hind leg. G, sculpture of metafemur. H, hind telotarsus. I, metasoma in dorsal view. J, apex of metasoma in lateral view. Abbreviation: fsa, falcate seta." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/375993/files/figure.png" pageId="21">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
J).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,188,1040]" pageId="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,342,583,608]" pageId="21">Recognition</emphasis>
. This species is easily separated from 
<taxonomicName box="[789,936,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subconica">
<emphasis box="[789,936,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="21">B. subconica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[995,1141,583,608]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[995,1141,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="21">Brachymeria</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
'Brassolis' by the smaller number of setae on the basal fold. It is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName box="[805,963,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="philornisae">
<emphasis box="[805,963,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="21">B. philornisae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1019,1167,620,645]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis box="[1019,1167,620,645]" italics="true" pageId="21">B. costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the antennal scrobes being virtually as high as the eye such that the upper edge is about level with the upper ocular line.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,188,1040]" pageId="21">
The ratios provided by the LDA extractor are also useful (Tab. 4 and Fig. 4). The ratios of 
<emphasis box="[1280,1417,692,717]" italics="true" pageId="21">head breath</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis box="[151,369,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="21">frontovertex breath</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[431,679,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="21">mesoscutellum breath</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis box="[708,991,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="21">median ocellus diameter</emphasis>
readily separate it from 
<taxonomicName box="[1284,1436,727,752]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subrugosa">
<emphasis box="[1284,1436,727,752]" italics="true" pageId="21">B. subrugosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
while the ratios of 
<emphasis box="[376,571,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="21">metasoma length</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis box="[600,798,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="21">mesosoma length</emphasis>
and 
<emphasis box="[860,997,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="21">head breath</emphasis>
: 
<emphasis box="[1027,1145,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="21">eye height</emphasis>
distinguish it from most specimens of 
<taxonomicName box="[305,452,799,824]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis box="[305,452,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="21">B. costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="21.[151,1437,188,1040]" pageId="21">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,266,836,861]" pageId="21">Hosts</emphasis>
. The 
<typeStatus box="[333,381,837,861]" pageId="21">type</typeStatus>
series and the female examined were both from 
<emphasis box="[940,1164,836,861]" italics="true" pageId="21">
<collectingRegion box="[940,1041,836,861]" country="United States of America" name="Alabama" pageId="21">Alabama</collectingRegion>
argillacea
</emphasis>
(Hübner) (
<taxonomicName box="[1291,1433,836,861]" class="Insecta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="order">Lepidoptera</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName box="[151,272,871,896]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Noctuidae</taxonomicName>
). The tachinid hosts quoted by 
<bibRefCitation author="De" box="[629,815,871,896]" pageId="21" refString="De Santis, L. (1967) Catalogo de los Himenopteros Argentinos de la Serie Parasitica, incluyendo Bethyloidea. Comision de Investigacion Cientificas, La Plata, Provincia de Buenos Aires, 337 pp." type="book" year="1967">De Santis (1967</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Santis" box="[828,885,872,896]" pageId="21" refString="De Santis, L. (1979) Catalogo de los himenopteros calcidoideos de America al sur de los Estados Unidos. Comision de Investigaciones Cientificas Provincia de Buenos Aires, Publicacion Especial, 488 pp." type="book" year="1979">1979</bibRefCitation>
) must be checked because of the past confusion concerning the identity of the species. This species was erroneously quoted as 
<taxonomicName box="[1036,1182,908,933]" class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="subconica">
<emphasis box="[1036,1182,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="21">B. subconica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by 
<bibRefCitation box="[1224,1436,908,933]" pageId="21" refString="Silvie, P. J., Delvare, G., Aberlenc H. - P., Prudent, P., Santana, H. J., Gomez, V. A., Cardozo, R. &amp; Michel, B. (2014) Diversite des Arthropodes rencontres en culture cotonniere au Paraguay. 2. Insectes predateurs, parasitoides et hyperparasitoides. Entomologie Faunistique - Faunistic Entomology, 67, 179 - 191." type="journal article">
Silvie 
<emphasis box="[1297,1354,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="21">et al.</emphasis>
(2014)
</bibRefCitation>
and at least some of the hosts cited by the authors are probably erroneous because the species was mixed with 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Chalcididae" genus="Brachymeria" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="21" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="costalimai">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="21">B. costalimai</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as noted above.
</paragraph>
